    "abstract": "<jats:p> This paper develops a theory that explains why financial crises follow profitable lending booms. When agents exhibit the \u201cavailability heuristic\u201d and there is a long period of banking profitability, all agents\u2014banks, their investors, and regulators\u2014end up in an \u201cavailability cascade,\u201d overestimating bankers' risk-management skills and underestimating the probability that observed outcomes are due to good luck. Consequently, banks profitably invest in riskier assets. Subsequently, if a public signal reveals that outcomes are luck-driven, investors withdraw funds, liquidity evaporates, and a crisis ensues. A loan resale market improves liquidity but increases the probability of a crisis. </jats:p>",
